        <section>
            <h2>What is the Agile Model?</h2>
            <p>
                The Agile Model is a modern software development approach designed to handle change and deliver software quickly. It was introduced in the 1990s to address limitations of traditional methods like the Waterfall Model, which made it difficult and expensive to modify requirements during development. Agile focuses on flexibility, collaboration, and continuous improvement. Instead of completing the entire project at once, development happens in small cycles called iterations, allowing teams to deliver working versions of the software more frequently.
            </p>
        </section>
        <img src="img/agile.png" alt="Agile Cheeta Image" class="agile-image">
        <section>
            <h2>How the Agile Process Works</h2>
            <p>
               The Agile process combines iterative and incremental development, meaning the software is built gradually through repeated cycles. Each cycle includes several important steps. First, the team gathers requirements and works with customers to understand their needs. Next, the system is designed and developers begin building features during short development cycles, often called sprints. After coding, the software is tested to ensure that each feature works correctly. Once testing is complete, the new version of the software is deployed to users. Feedback from customers and stakeholders is then collected, and this feedback is used to improve the next development cycle. 
            </p>
        </section>
        <section>
            <h2>Advantages and Use Cases</h2>
            <p>
                The Agile Model is valued for its flexibility and focus on customer feedback. Because development happens in small increments, teams can quickly adjust to changing requirements and continuously improve the software. Agile works best for projects where requirements may change or evolve over time. It is commonly used in modern software development environments where teams need to release updates quickly and respond to user feedback throughout the project
            </p>
        </section>
